<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Vaccinium</i> <i>cespitosum</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub and herbaceous layers with <i>Botrychium</i> <i>simplex</i>, <i>Calamagrostis</i> <i>muiriana</i>, <i>Carex</i> <i>nigricans</i>, <i>Danthonia</i> <i>intermedia</i>, <i>Danthonia</i> <i>unispicata</i>, <i>Kalmia</i> <i>microphylla</i>, <i>Luzula</i> <i>comosa</i>, <i>Pedicularis</i> <i>attollens</i>, <i>Phyllodoce</i> <i>breweri</i>, <i>Poa</i> <i>stebbinsii</i>, <i>Ptilagrostis</i> <i>kingii</i>, <i>Salix</i> <i>orestera</i> and <i>Saxifraga</i> <i>aprica</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Pinus</i> <i>contorta</i> ssp. <i>murrayana</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 0.5 m; canopy is open to
continuous. Herbaceous layer is variable. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Vaccinium cespitosum</i> and graminoids are the principal cover in the dwarf shrub and herbaceous layers (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
		
		<li><i>Vaccinium cespitosum</i> or <i>Kalmia microphylla</i> > 5% absolute cover in the dwarf shrub layer (Potter 2005).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> High elevation mesic to dry meadows, terraces, benches, basins, near snowbanks, or along the shores of ponds. Soils are generally granitic in origin and seasonally saturated. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Vaccinium cespitosum</i> as a FACW plant. </div>
</div>

        
