<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Vaccinium cespitosum </i>is a dwarf to mat-forming, rhizomatous shrub to 50 cm tall. Twigs are muchbranched, angled stems that are green, tan, or red, becoming brownish-gray with age. Leaves are deciduous. Berries are dark blue to black with a glaucous bloom. Seeds are not dormant and require no stratification. Birds and mammals disperse the seeds (Tirmenstein 1990a). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Vaccinium cespitosum </i>as a species is widely distributed on dry and wet sites from Mexico to Alaska, across southern Canada, in the Great Lakes region, in New England, and in eastern Canada. It also is wide-ranging in California, including San Bruno Mountain, Point Reyes National Seashore, Humboldt Co. coastline, and the mountains in northern to eastern California. Plants are upright shrubs at low elevations in California, but they are typically mat-forming plants in meadows at subalpine and alpine elevations in the central and southern Sierra Nevada (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). The names <i>V. arbuscula </i>and <i>V. nivictum </i>appear in some California references for this species. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance often occurs at forest edges, ponds, and lakes where shrubs typically cover the ground surface in moderate to dense cover; though sometimes the herbaceous cover is dominant and shrubs are open and scattered. When <i>V. cespitosum </i>occurs at varying cover with <i>K. microphylla, Calamagrostis muiriana, </i>and other sedges, we have placed the stands here; when <i>V. cespitosum </i>occurs as a co-dominant with <i>P. breweri, </i>we place the stands in the <i>Phyllodoce breweri </i>alliance. We need more sampling and analysis to understand the relationships among these alliances that are treated variously by different authors (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b, Potter 2005). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
